    id: 'curated-anime-character-design-sheet-template',
    title: 'Anime Character Design Sheet Template',
    category: 'Storyboards',
    prompt: `【Worldview】
Enter here

【Number of People】
Enter here

【Roles/Functions】
Enter here

【Overall Atmosphere】
Enter here

【Features of That World】
Enter here

【Things to Emphasize】
Enter here

【Things to Avoid】
Enter here

【Differentiation Instructions】
Enter here

【Illustration Tone】
Smooth line art, flat anime coloring, subtle cel-shading, shadows in one stage only, no gradients, no thick painting, no realistic texture rendering, no strong light and shadow effects, a flat look that''s easy to animate

【Anime Conversion Instructions】
While maintaining the original design''s structure, motifs, color scheme, and roles, simplify the rendering for use in an anime main series. Use flat anime coloring for fills, and limit shadows to one stage only. Avoid gradients, soft shading, thick painting effects, and overly delicate material depictions. For semi-transparent materials or thin fabrics, render them not with realistic textures but in a cel-animated style organized by flat surfaces.

Based on the input above, please create an image in the style of original anime character setting materials.

Purpose:
To create characters driven by costume design, rooted in the worldview. Express the character''s personality not through faces or hairstyles, but through clothing, equipment, materials, structure, color schemes, silhouettes, and cultural symbols.

Most Important:
Extract the unique visual rules of that world and reflect them in both the clothing and the layout. Make it not just generic fantasy, but "clothing born in this world."

Differentiation Rules:
For each character and each worldview proposal, ensure the following do not overlap:
1. Silhouette
2. Main Material
3. Color Scheme Rules
4. Equipment Structure
5. Cultural Symbols
6. Clothing Purpose
7. Page Design Atmosphere

Design Conditions:
- Roles or positions should be conveyed through appearance
- Reflect the worldview''s culture, environment, systems, beliefs, and technology in the clothing
- Make decorations meaningful
- Create silhouettes identifiable from a distance
- Do not differentiate solely by faces or hairstyles
- Maintain a sense of unity as inhabitants of the same world while clearly distinguishing roles

Key Focus for Costume Design:
- Give clear distinctive features to the silhouette
- Infuse worldview-appropriate qualities into the materials
- Assign meaning to colors
- Add distinctive features to fasteners, overlaps, storage, accessories, movable parts
- Include practical items that indicate roles or purposes
- Incorporate world-specific cultural symbols

Things to Avoid:
- generic fantasy armor
- generic mage robe
- generic RPG hero design
- too many belts
- random accessories
- overused capes
- standard medieval fantasy template
- looks similar to existing anime IPs
- similar multi-layered outfits regardless of worldview
- similar color schemes or hanging decorations regardless of worldview

Image Presentation:
- High resolution
- Anime style
- Delicate line art
- Clean cel shading
- In the style of official setting materials or concept art sheets
- Full-body standing pose
- Include small costume detail diagrams or equipment sketches as appropriate
- Minimal titles, numbers, short English labels
- Prioritize visuals with minimal text

Layout:
Vary the page design to match the worldview.
- Administrative/Institutional: Linear, organized, like forms or standard diagrams
- Sea/Wind/Pilgrimage: Flowing compositions with open space, like tide charts or route maps
- Underground/Organic: Rounded, layered organic diagrams
- Travel/Nomadic: Focus on portable items, carrying structures, back views
- Industrial/Logistics: Emphasis on structural diagrams, exploded views, tool details

Most Important:
Not mass-produced fantasy—create designs that convey the origins of the clothing, materials, purposes, and cultural meanings. For different worldviews, make it instantly clear they belong to entirely different systems.`,
